/pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/documentation/v0.4.27-alpha/archive/</guid><description>PLAKAR-ARCHIVE(1) - General Commands Manual</description></item><item><title>agent</title><link>https://plakar.io/documentation/main/agent/</link><pubDate>Tue, 18 Feb 2025 19:59:32 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/documentation/main/agent/</guid><description>Run the Plakar agent</description></item><item><title>agent</title><link>https://plakar.io/documentation/v0.4.27-alpha/agent/</link><pubDate>Tue, 18 Feb 2025 19:39:57 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/documentation/v0.4.27-alpha/agent/</guid><description>PLAKAR-AGENT(1) - General Commands Manual</description></item><item><title>Understanding RTO and RPO in disaster recovery</title><link>https://plakar.io/insights/understanding-rto-and-rpo-in-disaster-recovery/</link><pubDate>Tue, 11 Feb 2025 02:11:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/insights/understanding-rto-and-rpo-in-disaster-recovery/</guid><description>&lt;p>In today‚Äôs digital landscape, where &lt;strong>downtime can cost businesses thousands of dollars per minute&lt;/strong>, having a robust &lt;strong>disaster recovery (DR) strategy&lt;/strong> is non-negotiable. Two fundamental metrics in any &lt;strong>business continuity plan&lt;/strong> are &lt;strong>recovery time objective (RTO)&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>recovery point objective (RPO)&lt;/strong>. These determine how quickly a system can recover after a failure and how much data a company is willing to lose in the process.&lt;/p></description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://plakar.io/insights/understanding-rto-and-rpo-in-disaster-recovery/feature.svg"/></item><item><title>S3 is not a backup: why you need a real backup strategy</title><link>https://plakar.io/insights/s3-is-not-a-backup---why-you-need-a-real-backup-strategy/</link><pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2025 15:12:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/insights/s3-is-not-a-backup---why-you-need-a-real-backup-strategy/</guid><description>&lt;p>Let us get straight to the point: Amazon S3 is a phenomenal service for scalable, reliable object storage but it is not a backup solution. Sure, S3 boasts rock-solid durability and cost efficiency, but relying on it alone for backups is like trying to cover your bases with duct tape. In today‚Äôs world, where a single misclick can spell disaster, a thoughtful, multi-layered backup strategy is not just nice to have; it is absolutely essential.&lt;/p></description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://plakar.io/insights/s3-is-not-a-backup---why-you-need-a-real-backup-strategy/feature.png"/></item><item><title>Why replication is not backup</title><link>https://plakar.io/insights/why-replication-is-not-backup/</link><pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2025 15:02:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/insights/why-replication-is-not-backup/</guid><description>&lt;p>In the realm of data protection, &lt;strong>backup&lt;/strong> and &lt;strong>replication&lt;/strong> are two fundamental strategies employed to safeguard information. While they share the common goal of data preservation, they operate on distinct principles and serve different purposes. Understanding these differences is crucial for developing a robust data protection strategy.&lt;/p></description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://plakar.io/insights/why-replication-is-not-backup/featured.webp"/></item><item><title>The 3-2-1 backup rule: A proven strategy for data protection</title><link>https://plakar.io/insights/the-3-2-1-backup-rule---a-proven-strategy-for-data-protection/</link><pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2025 14:24:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/insights/the-3-2-1-backup-rule---a-proven-strategy-for-data-protection/</guid><description>&lt;p>Data loss can happen in many ways: whether due to accidental deletion, cyberattacks, hardware failure, or even a catastrophic event like a &lt;strong>data center fire&lt;/strong>. To protect against these risks, IT professionals have long relied on the &lt;strong>3-2-1 backup rule&lt;/strong>, a fundamental strategy for ensuring data resilience.&lt;/p></description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://plakar.io/insights/the-3-2-1-backup-rule---a-proven-strategy-for-data-protection/featured.png"/></item><item><title>Legal Notice</title><link>https://plakar.io/legal-notice/</link><pubDate>Wed, 18 Dec 2024 10:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/legal-notice/</guid><description>Publisher # Plakar Simplified Joint-Stock Company (SAS) with a capital of 1,000 euros SIREN: 933 509 754 RCS Paris Head office: 149 avenue du Maine, 75014 Paris, France EU VAT number: FR XX 933509754 Host: KANDBAZ SAS, 1 rue de Stockholm, 75008 Paris, France</description></item><item><title>Team</title><link>https://plakar.io/team/team/</link><pubDate>Wed, 18 Dec 2024 10:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/team/team/</guid><description>Hello teams</description></item><item><title>Plakar Hackroom Highlights: New Faces, Fresh Fixes, and UI Upgrades üêøÔ∏è</title><link>https://plakar.io/community-news/2024-11_01/</link><pubDate>Wed, 13 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/community-news/2024-11_01/</guid><description>Hello Plakar pals and curious coders!</description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://plakar.io/community-news/2024-11_01/featured.webp"/></item><item><title>Plakar Hackroom Highlights: New Features, Fresh Faces, and Big Ideas üêøÔ∏è</title><link>https://plakar.io/community-news/2024-11_02/</link><pubDate>Wed, 13 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0100</pubDate><guid>https://plakar.io/community-news/2024-11_02/</guid><description>Hello Plakar pals and curious coders!</description><media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://plakar.io/community-news/2024-11_02/featured.webp"/></item><item><title>Plakup's Chronicles: A Journey Th